Create PUMA - COVID Crosswalk

COVID neighborhoods do not conform to tracts or other census geographies.

The neighborhoods being used for COVID are smaller than PUMAs (there are ~304 neighborhoods vs. 69 PUMAs). The goal is to crosswalk neighborhoods to PUMAs and then aggregate COVID cases to PUMAs.

Step 1. Intersect PUMAs and COVID Neighborhood geometries

Prepare for intersect: Calculate area of COVID neighborhoods

# calc area of covid sp area
covid$area_neighb <- st_area(covid)

# calculate area of pumas
puma$area_puma <- st_area(puma)

# st_write(covid, "covid_polys.geojson", driver = "GeoJSON")
# st_write(puma, "puma_polys.geojson", driver = "GeoJSON")

# st_write(covid, "covid_polys.shp", driver = "ESRI Shapefile")
# st_write(puma, "puma_polys.shp", driver = "ESRI Shapefile")

Intersect COVID And PUMAs

# intersect 
int <- st_intersection(covid, puma)

Step 2. Calculate area of intersecting polygons

# calc area of intersect
int$area_int <- st_area(int)

Step 3. Calculate percent overlap of intersecting area with tract

How much of the neighborhood intersects with the PUMA?

EX: If 50% of the neighborhood intersects with a PUMA, that PUMA gets 50% of their COVID cases.

# % intersect
int$prc_int <- as.numeric(int$area_int/int$area_neighb)

Proportional Allocation of COVID Cases

Step 1. Join Crosswalk and Multiply Cases by % Intersect

# join crosswalk to covid cases
covid_xwalk <- 
covid %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  select(-area_neighb) %>% 
  
  # join crosswalk
  full_join(xwalk, by="lac_place_name") %>% 
  
  # multiply prc intersect to covid cases 
  mutate(prop_cases = confirmed_cases * prc_int)

The number of COVID cases in a community have been proportionally allocated to PUMAs. Sum cases by PUMA.

Quick basic diagnostic to verify the data tells us what we expect:

corr_eqrank <- cor.test(wc_covid$sum_cases, wc_covid$equityindex_ranks)

corr_eqrank
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  wc_covid$sum_cases and wc_covid$equityindex_ranks
## t = -4.5211, df = 67, p-value = 0.00002572
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.6462240 -0.2787055
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## -0.483493

  • Correlation of -0.48 is a fairly strong negative correlation between COVID cases and equity ranks. Since equity rank = 1 is the highest need, a negative correlation means that as COVID cases increase, equity rank decreases–indicates higher need.

  • Also we see this correlation is statistically significant.

Typology Test 1

Use existing Whole Child type rankings (highes to lowest), grouped into three categories.

# group quintiles
wc_covid$group_rank <- ifelse(wc_covid$rankingtype %in% c("Highest", "High"),
                              "High/Highest", 
                              ifelse(wc_covid$rankingtype %in% c("Lowest", "Low"),
                                     "Low/Lowest", wc_covid$rankingtype))


# summarize -- get average and median by groups 
dat_grp <- 
wc_covid %>% 
  group_by(group_rank) %>% 
  summarize(mean = mean(sum_cases, na.rm = T),
            median = median(sum_cases, na.rm = T))

dat_grp
## # A tibble: 3 x 3
##   group_rank    mean median
##   <chr>        <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1 High/Highest 1143.   987.
## 2 Low/Lowest    591.   541.
## 3 Moderate      836.   768.

Plot: COVID case density by grouped rankings

Overall, PUMAs with the lowest need are more likely to be areas with lower COVID cases. PUMAs with highest need are more likely to be areas with higher COVID cases.

  • Average COVID case count for PUMAs with high/highest Whole Child ranking is 1,143.3, 1.9 times higher than the average COVID case count for PUMAs with the low/lowest Whole Child ranking.

  • The average number of COVID cases for PUMAs with moderate Whole Child ranking is 835.8, 1.4 times higher than the average COVID case count for PUMAs with the low/lowest Whole Child ranking.

# make grouped ranks ordered factors
wc_covid$group_rank_fac <- factor(wc_covid$group_rank, ordered = TRUE,
                                   levels = c("High/Highest", "Moderate", "Low/Lowest")) 

# plot grouped ranks
ggplot(wc_covid, aes(sum_cases)) +
  geom_density(aes(fill=factor(group_rank_fac)), alpha = 0.6)+
   geom_vline(data = dat_grp, aes(xintercept = mean), linetype="dashed", size=1) +
  labs(title = "Density of PUMAs by Number of Confirmed COVID Cases",
       subtitle = "Grouped by Whole Child Equity Index Ranking.\nVertical lines indicate group means.") +
  ylab("Density of PUMAs") +
  theme_minimal()

Typology Test 3: Equity ranks by quartile

Classify equity ranks by quartile

wc_covid <-
  wc_covid %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(eqind_quart = ntile(equityindex_ranks, 4))

table(wc_covid$eqind_quart, useNA = "always")

Maybe won’t use quartiles of equity index ranks…seems like we already have the typology from the source data (quintiles), and quartiles of the equity ranks means that some 2nd quintle (high need) PUMAs get grouped in with the third quartile of equity ranks..which doesn’t seem good/no reason to reclassify already classified pumas?

ggplot(wc_covid, aes(sum_cases)) +
  geom_density(aes(fill=factor(eqind_quart)), alpha = 0.6)+
  theme_minimal()

^^ I don’t think this plot is good.

library(ggrepel)

ggplot(test, 
      aes(x= equityindex_ranks_rev, y=sum_cases)) +

                  aes(label=test[test$pumace10 %in% c("03701","03765", "03744", "03769"),]$label),  size = 2)+
